{{short description|Adage}} [[File:Stop Digging ^ - geograph.org.uk - 195319.jpg|upright=1.15|thumb|right|An [[excavator]] that is in a hole and has stopped [[digging]]|alt=Photograph of a backhoe that is over fifty percent submerged in a large hole that it dug in a peat bog before falling in.]] The '''first law of holes''', or the '''law of holes''', is an [[adage]] which states that "if you find yourself in a hole, stop digging".<ref name=wordsworth/><ref name=interview/> Digging a hole makes it deeper and therefore harder to get back out, which is used as a metaphor that when in an untenable position, it is best to stop carrying on and exacerbating the situation.
==Attribution== The adage has been attributed to a number of sources. It appeared in print on page six of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' dated October 25, 1911, in the form: "Nor would a wise man, seeing that he was in a hole, go to work and blindly dig it deeper..."<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Dictionary of Modern Proverbs|publisher=[[Yale University Press]]|location=New Haven|year=2012|isbn=9780300136029|first1=Charles Clay|last1=Doyle|first2=Wolfgang|last2=Mieder|first3=Fred R.|last3=Shapiro}}</ref> In ''[[The Bankers magazine]]'', it was published in 1964 as: "Let me tell you about the law of holes: If you find yourself in a hole, stop digging."<ref>{{Cite journal|journal=The Bankers Magazine|page=61|title=Is That Dirt Being Shovelled?|volume=166|year=1964}}</ref>
In the United Kingdom, it has been referred to as "Healey's first law of holes"<ref name=interview>{{cite journal|last1=Lloyd|first1=John|last2=Hargreaves|authorlink2=Ian Hargreaves|authorlink1=John Lloyd (journalist)|first2=Ian|title=Interview: Denis Healey; Healey's first law of holes is to stop digging|journal=[[New Statesman]]|date=8 November 1996|volume=9|url=http://business.highbeam.com/794/article-1G1-19124747/healey-first-law-holes-stop-digging-so-he-believes|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140728102235/http://business.highbeam.com/794/article-1G1-19124747/healey-first-law-holes-stop-digging-so-he-believes|url-status=dead|archive-date=28 July 2014|accessdate=25 July 2014|via=[[HighBeam Research|HighBeam Business]]}}</ref> after politician [[Denis Healey]], who used the adage in the 1980s and later.<ref name=wordsworth>{{cite book|last=Apperson|first=George Latimer|title=The Wordsworth Dictionary of Proverbs|year=2006|publisher=Wordsworth Editions|location=Ware|isbn=978-1840223118|page=283|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7PMZJqSR4sAC&lpg=PA283&dq=%22first%20law%20of%20holes%22%20Healy&pg=PA283#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> Some sources misattribute the phrase to American humorist [[Will Rogers]].<ref>[http://www.parks.ca.gov/?page_id=23998 Will Rogers Legacy]. ''California Department of Parks and Recreation''</ref>
